\section*{Pathophysiology:}

\section*{The cryptoglandular hypothesis}

The infection begins in cryptoglandular situated at the dentate line in the anal canal and progresses into the muscular wall of the anal sphincters to cause an anorectal abscess.
Following surgical or spontaneous drainage in the perianal skin, occasionally a granulation tissue-lined tract is left behind, forming the fistula in-ano which causes recurrent symptoms.

\section*{Classification of fistula in-ano}

\section*{Parks classification system}

The Parks classification system defines 4 types of fistula-in-ano that result from cryptoglandular infections.

\section*{1.Intersphincteric-commonest-70\%}

Common course - Via internal sphincter to the intersphincteric space and then to the perineum. They result from perianal abscesses

\section*{2. Transsphincteric $\mathbf{- 2 5 \%}$}

Common course - Low via internal and external sphincters into the ischiorectal fossa and then to the perineum. Originate from ischiorectal abscesses

\section*{3.Suprasphincteric $\mathbf{- 5 \%}$}

Common course - Via intersphincteric space superiorly to above puborectalis muscle into ischiorectal fossa and then to perineum. Result from supralevator abscesses

\section*{4. Extrasphincteric-1\%}

Bypass the anal canal and sphincter mechanism, passing through the ischiorectal fossa and levator ani muscle, and open high in the rectum
