\section*{-Relevant Anatomy:}

The urethra is divided into anterior and posterior segments. The anterior urethra (from distal to proximal) includes the meatus, fossa navicularis, penile or pendulous urethra, and bulbar urethra.
It lies within the corpus spongiosum, beginning at the level of the bulbous urethra and extending distally through the length of the penile urethra.
-The bulbar urethra begins at the root of the penis and ends at the urogenital diaphragm.
-The penile urethra has a more central position within the corpus spongiosum in contrast to the bulbous urethra, which is more dorsally positioned
The posterior urethra (from distal to proximal) includes the membranous urethra and the prostatic urethra.
